One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in the same line, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 election, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced during 2011 restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an ID with a photograph, as well as proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of counting, and withdraw their right to vote for citizens with criminal records.
Prior to the 2006 election, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
That's why republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack such an identity document.
But often, obtaining the required ID costs more than a hundred dollars.
Therefore, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people on low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters between the age of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, voters who vote for Democratic candidates the most, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs that often vote Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic voting.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers supported in 2011 certain laws that denies voter registration on the same day as counting in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to assist voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 made the registration rate for new voters fall in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of voters, equivalent to 24% of citizens voting in advance.
However, white people, who make up 76% of the electorate, account for no more than 46% of citizens voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this sense, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed at the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say for sure whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will adversely affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
