Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, as the chances of getting it wrong seem slim. We'll see what it's all about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also such a law: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicist classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who obey wisely at the beginning of Pauli.
