According to Berkeley Laboratories' the Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be in some way related.
These bosons, you could stress here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" that acts as a "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we threw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force carrier" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
