Each transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public account book, which is broadcast throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through solving a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of interim central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file hashing phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (plus zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundredth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
"The ruling used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Insitito Weizmann in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, the "giant rebates" were launched.
"$30,000 has been changed," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to launch in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of review of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take a while for Bitcoin to impose, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
