A Forceps Constitution in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times amended, for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial messs.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "betray his word" and "trampl the law."
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis faster and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this resource has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote on my text or I maintain the full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist for the most part, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not go to the call.
By mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they believed they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, substitute members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As you might expect, the articles voted on have been unanimous.
Commentators are also pleased that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all eyes, remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "the rules", which would have allowed stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than an advertising ruse.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who is to confirm its conformity with sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing that "people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The liberals' fears are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be considerably less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the marital state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But it acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted on yesterday has received much criticism that relates to the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will argue that there are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another point of contentious: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will prosecutions of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also expressed concerns regarding the text, which they consider liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy remains and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
