Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families who have stayed home.
From 1 December a law enters into force, according to which each labour immigrant must take an examination to verify their knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those intending to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to take the examination of the language, but also that of Russian history and that of the basics of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must even be confirmed in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Citizens of countries where Russian is the official language are an exception.
The people who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will be sponsored by the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the test in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the exam was supported by Deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the obligation of knowledge of the language bring to both Russians and immigrants themselves?
First, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labour immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defence of your rights must be initiated before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are for immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, put a "paid journey" into a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him consume for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," confirms the Head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajikistan Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be mad, little boss!
In the meantime, however, many citizens of central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also in their own language they write with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to mention dressing them, wearing them and buying them what is necessary for the school.
As they reach adolescence, these kids venture to work at the first opportunity.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, as far as the law on language is concerned, rights defenders point to an important point.
Exams will be conducted only for immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause is in the bureaucratic obstacles and in the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be done quickly and for only a thousand and five hundred rubles.
Russian police employees know that we usually carry fake documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"We are asked for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajikistan citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several "false" certificates of language knowledge have already been seized by Federal Immigration Service officials.
