Iimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in just under a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It's just one of many other alarmist news we like to hold on to.
The tap tap group likes to make jokes about this rather and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you organize a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a state charity act that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Maya calendar set out for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December at 21 hours, we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on Kiribati Island in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we forged the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, T-shirts, bags and original keychains against the end of the world that can be purchased in www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, titled "End of the World, Cancelled".
It is currently very popular on YouTube, can it be heard at charity concerts?
Of course it is, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time at all three concerts.
The anthems will link with each other simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
He has written the lyrics to this song and plays the starring role of Jesus in the video clip, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We work together even with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We put all our efforts into participating in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and amused to work with us.
What will the money raised in the concerts go to against the end of the world?
To equipment for the studeo barrier-free educational center, which we completed in its sixth consecutive year with the tap civil association in Jedli.k.v ústav.
The students of the school in Jedlisekv ústav regularly receive the visit of teachers with those who carry out fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make this possible.
In the context of the completion of the works in Jedlisekv ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
In each concert several groups and performers perform.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to develop a program that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jisí Sucho will perform in Prague.
For more detailed information, you can www.kpks.cz.
Do you plan for any other similar "spectacular action" in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Praske jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of the us being in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have acted for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
What is the logistics and organization of these trips like?
It's not as hard as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. ASA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to amaze me.
Even in Moscow, where we came back from recently, everything came out without problems.
Thanks to the outings abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you come across so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still not often that a person moves alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, to give preference to someone in a wheelchair by elevator, there it is not.
Luckily, a civil association has been created that strives to theopathize the problems of people with disabilities.
In what respects should we take an example of more developed countries?
There are many aspects in which we go behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a serious disability to move on their own in public and to be able to go to the service, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it's not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap, we're a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, it will start to change everything for real.
So far, they are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look a few years ago, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I walked into Jedlisekv ústav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I am a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láca Angelovia says, we got a little out of hand (laughs).
However, popularity hasn't come until these last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that we were quite helped by connecting with famous singers and also working actively to promote the group.
We come to the conclusion that the work that is not seen, is as if it does not exist.
Thanks to the aid of the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that something else can be done.
Show business is full of things that look like each other.
It makes sense, in its own way, that everything new is cautiously welcomed and takes a long time to accept.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say that The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it is a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and those of us who must have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it is not only a breakthrough for them, but for the whole of society.
Did the fact that you're a demanding boss help, as a lot of people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many ways and demand some discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and with their heads in the clouds and when they learn that they have to go two days to rehearse, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, the initial euphoria leaves them quickly.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and get something.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were already in the early 1998s?
Only one: Láca Angelovia.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't help it.
