Poland and the cosmos.
Poland was accepted as a twelfth esa member at last week's meeting of ministers from European Space Agency countries. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in flights into space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference of A. Eternfeld at the Astronomical Observatory in Warsaw at which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left attendees indifferent and, years later, Aternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, he won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known around the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he named one of the craters on the hidden face of the moon.
As far back as 1925 a dresina was built in Poland and was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is unclear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the dresin or for braking.
Information about this dresin is limited to that collected in the press of the time.
From 1933 on, Polish artillery began to engage in missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by engineer Rohozi-ski appeared in the specialized press and the following year the studio "Rakieta - clumsy powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were aimed at the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technique projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine refers for the first time to society with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
One of them, prof.M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
Artificial satellite projects had already been launched at the time and it was obvious that cosmic research was a future-proof discipline.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first released on October 10, 1958.
The rocket was 1,800 meters high, about 80 cm long and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial testing of the two-stage RM-2 rockets was initiated in the desert of B.D.ów.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket under development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to peak at 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 liters, on the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum heyday in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first aerial tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the NATIONAL COMMITTEE of COSPAR two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the investigation of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonuta after Vladimír Remek.
