Architecture studio MVRDV shows that true adventures are not only in the lead - in the example of Spijkenisse's library and the newly completed "mountain of books"- 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there's finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby who walks down the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a large company near the library, says, "In addition, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and eBooks.
Nobody comes in for pleasure in those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory city at the gates of Rotterdam that is hardly worth a fleeting visit, holds the dubious honor of having come up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to general culture and to copy the seven fictitious bridges depicted on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how policy makers decided there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and seemed to present the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for spijkenisse's mountain of books, the so-called 'Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the intended location.
This is part of the revitalization project, complete with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
In this way, the small town devoid of history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy power plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a quesera.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with their topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to encompass with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant lampposts unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
As you look up, you can see the banks of the park, dogs and children playing football.
And books, books and more books everywhere.
"Usually the bookshelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we've done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area out of the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more a day shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And this is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we come across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, a plastic fabric of a few millimetres thick has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a basis for holding crop roots.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and is then thrown away.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until plates four centimeters thick were obtained.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mix of new car and sneakers.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the café you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed areas, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology," Trouborst says.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge pyramid of glass, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden trusses located in the cross-sectional direction to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a thing of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
Similarly, traditional Chinese medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul."
The reason is that, on the occasion of the opening that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This is intended to fill, for the moment, with the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete file; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows his book is part of the library.
Even if it's only there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a success in this discipline reigns that in specialized slang is known as "creating an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No more young and uneducated you may be.
Finally a starting point to form your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather dangerous diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany implied that it would vote against the proposal to grant Palestinian territories united Nations observer status.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship between the country and Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don't think it supports the American stance either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a flight ban zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is because it is currently reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to it.
I think they're still trying their part, but they've already started the path to a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy specifically mean from a German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend different positions than those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are somewhat different from those of other major powers and that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give it so much importance since it's not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by abstaining from voting in important decisions such as in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German stance enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps germany has managed to gain some respect.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
Instead, the U.S. has clearly been in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
There have always been these disparities due to American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend that position in public.
I believe that the real disparity of opinions does not really have the scale attributed to it.
Looking at relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the politics he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that's precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for germans if there was a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher er, but must drive things from their own position.
That's exactly what they're doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to take a European stance.
Of course this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a dangerous subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of independent figure.
