The Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest living levels, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country is related to its greed for a very smelly fish?
Take a series of over-cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowy. The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how smelly you prefer, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this delicacy of the most, so to speak, captivating.
"He eats raw and then drinks a glass of aquavit for a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk," who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking from a drink important amounts of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," Havard says.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I'll try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near your nose, it's not bad; it's not much different from a sushi serving that's traveled a few miles by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty plagued Norway and when, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the inactive senses due to alcohol, eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is increasing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not too much richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered important, an essential but rather smelly part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you the fridge of 10 euros ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it to do so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who gunned down and murdered 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 event."
Norwegians have a hard time believing that in their peaceful country one of their own would be able to commit such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she walks past trays of rakfisk and who, with her long blonde mane and amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, wise people."
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything except a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn't have during the years leading up to the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we're happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk, " he adds with a scrambled laugh.
I'm in the snow queuing for something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to savor.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a presenter who wears a bow tie and who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls off the chair, perhaps defeated by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a rough start
