Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with Allegations of Bradley Manning's Abuse during his time in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution's interrogation of Manning in a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits by unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request that the case be dismissed since his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already been sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of killing himself while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein checked with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was imprisoned on a maximum detention course from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment given to him by the wardens as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any allegations of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that visiting officials had discussed these issues and indicated to him that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record these issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I hadn't mentioned any problems," Manning said.
Justice, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council to examine the suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is one degree below that of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the General Staff to know that I was ok and (wanted) to stop being under injury prevention. to be able to enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday of his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that he once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said the fact that he wasn't allowed to know what was happening to him or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unac company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed he always had a light coming from outside pointing at his eyes in his sleep.
He said if the wardens couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about a plea she had made in Thursday's statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in her Quantico cell for a night, she was forced during a morning recount to stand unsymoutly in front of the wardens and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the recount.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the warden's order that he should drop the blanket he might have covered himself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or flip flops to self-harm but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers are hopeful that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted on the court-martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning convicted of misdemeanors and defend other allegations deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detainee in maximum custody in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
